        "creation_date": 1562331695,
        "body": "<p>The problem is that \" and \\ are both special characters. In order to use them as literals in strings, you need to escape them. So the correct way would be:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>str = str.replace(\"\\\"\", \"\\\\\\\"\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>In this context the strings are broken down as such, with spaces around the characters or clarity:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\" \\\" \" This is an escaped quote\n\" \\\\ \" This is an escaped backslash\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Thus if you want to represent a backslash followed by a quote, you can see that is breaks down as:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\" \\\\ \\\" \" Quotes around the whole literal, an escaped backslash, an escaped quote\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
        "answer_id": 56903603,
